node.text:
Morning meds for a kitten with kidney disease ♥️

Ferguson is thriving on this medication routine, and the best part is that he actually enjoys it! I wanted to share this sped-up look at what meds and supplements he takes every morning (and also how he takes them) in case that is helpful or interesting to you.

I use Ferguson’s favorite treats to motivate him to participate in med time. As you can see, he knows the routine and actually looks forward to these sessions! There is no one right way to work with kittens who need this much medication, but my approach is to see what works best for him, to keep everything as positive as possible, and to make adjustments as needed.

Here is what you’re seeing in the video:
-Subcutaneous fluids (LRS) with a 25g butterfly needle
-Injectable famotidine (an antacid, commonly known as Pepcid) which can be given with fluids
-Azodyl (a probiotic supporting renal health) mixed with churu
-Porous One (a uremic toxin binder) mixed with churu
-Orbax (an antibiotic)
-Clavamox (an antibiotic)
-Aluminum hydroxide (a phosphorous binder)
-He also gets injectable Cerenia (an antiemetic) which I do during his PM meds, so you don’t see that here

Please remember every case is different and you are advised to meet with a veterinary nephrology specialist to determine the right treatment for your kitten or cat! All of the medication given in this video is given under the guidance of Ferguson’s veterinary team.

🎶: The Album Leaf

node.text:
Nothing could warm my heart more than watching Ferguson play with Spud & the Buds! Here is 4 minutes of sweet playtime footage taken just a few minutes ago.

Fergie is 12 weeks old, while Spud & the Buds are about 5 weeks old…but due to his size and fragility they match really nicely for playtime. Now that the little ones are all healthy and past a nice long quarantine period, I felt comfortable letting him interact with them, and as you can see he is loving every minute!

Sadly, Ferguson is showing some physical signs of late stage kidney failure. To be completely honest, I have cried about it a lot over the past 24 hours. But then I’ll walk in the room and see him playing like this—or see him eat a big breakfast (more than half a can today!) and the only thing I can feel is happiness and hope. In spite of all he’s going through, he has such spunk and such a strong will to live a joyful life. I admire that about him so much. ♥️

#chimpytender

UPDATE: SHE FOUND A HOME!!! ♥️ Can we all come together and help this incredible senior gal?! Skyy is 20 years old(!) but doesn’t act a day over 10. She’s loving, affectionate, and impeccably fluffy. Skyy was well-loved for her entire life, but her human recently passed away and she ended up at the humane society. She so deserves a wonderful home to live out her golden years! Will you share her video & tag friends in Southern California who might be interested in her?

Skyy is adoptable from San Diego Humane Society. Let’s boost her story & help find her an amazing home! ♥️ @sdhumanesociety

Today we took in a new foster kitten! Spud is a tiny kitten the size & development of a 5-7 day old, but if you can believe this…he’s actually 16 days old! He was born very prematurely when his mama, a feral cat, came into our local TNR clinic @feral_cat_coalition in a trap. He was the only kitten born, and his mama was not able to care for him, so he was raised for the past two weeks by the clinic manager, @aud_everything_is_taken. Audrey reached out and asked if we had any interest in taking him on, and of course, we said HECK YES!

His former foster name was Bruno, but since we have already raised a baby Bruno, we collectively decided to name him after what he looks like most — a chonky potato. As you can see, he has an incredible appetite and a rotund belly! Audrey, you did a beautiful job getting him through his most vulnerable weeks, and I’m so happy we can help carry the baton from here to adoption.

Welcome, Spud Spudley! We love you!🥔

Every day is #GingerCatAppreciationDay now that I have Ferguson in my life! 🧡🧡🧡

Ferguson updates:
-He is 18 weeks old now!
-He weighs 3 pounds 10 ounces! Whaaat!
-He thinks that Andrew and I are cat trees that he can climb and perch on. He will scale our legs or hop right onto our shoulders, often when we least expect it!
-He can now run the entire catio, including climbing the 8 foot scratching post & hanging out on the highest perch.
-He is a total water boy & is obsessed with our sink.
-He loved having foster kitten friends, but since they were adopted out, he has been much more playful with Haroun. He loves friends!
-He has seen our new kittens, and he actually hissed at first (I think he was just very confused!) but now he likes to sit outside of their enclosure and watch them. They are only 3 weeks old, so he doesn’t have much in common with them, but he likes to supervise feedings.
-He is maintaining hydration better now, and gets fluids only every-other-day. On his days off, he is so confused and will meow and run to the couch to try to remind us!
-He still sleeps with us, often halfway under the covers or sharing my pillow with me.
-If his behavior, appetite, and growth are any indication, I expect to have a positive update at his nephrology appointment next week. He is thriving!

Photo by @iamthecatphotographer (go look at his post of Fergie drinking from the sink today—it’s adorable!) #chimpytender

node.text: To foster a kitten is to raise someone’s future best friend. How cool is that? I think about how much I love Coco, and then I look upon this miniature version of her and just marvel at the fact that he will one day be someone’s world, too. How amazing that I get to know Wolfman before his future family even knows him! It’s like cat-sitting, but preemptively. What a rewarding task, to keep him safe and warm until his forever can begin. 🖤 #fosteringsaveslives

Monday morning weigh-in! From extra-smollest to bigger-smollest, here are the current weights of the babies.

Extra-smols:
Candyman — 300g
Norman — 304g

Smols:
Samara — 338g
Carrie —364g
Wolfman — 373g

Bigger-smols:
Chucky — 402g
Babadook — 405g

As you can see, there is a difference of over 100g between the tiniest and largest kittens in this litter. But that’s okay! When weighing kittens (which you should do throughout the day at this age), you should be monitoring their individual progress, not measuring them against the progress of their siblings. As long as individual weights are steadily increasing (7-14g daily on average for neonates), that’s what matters! ♥️

node.text:
✨ C a t n a p ✨

This might me my favorite photo @iamthecatphotographer has ever taken of me. It is such an honest shot. No lipstick, no smiling for the camera, just a real moment he captured so beautifully. The sun was going down on a long day and I fell asleep on our oversized chair, joined by Fergie, Daisy, Ranger & Haroun. If social media asks the question “how are you?”, smiling photos falsely answer, “I’m fine,” but we all know that the real answer to that question is always more complicated than that. This photo feels like as true an answer as I could ever give: this year has been filled with such a combination of surreal quietude, existential sadness, deep gratitude, and dizzying expectations of the self that I sometimes end the day early just to quiet my brain and connect with the cats. I’m not sure exactly what I’m trying to say here…simply an acknowledgement that the past year and a half have taken every single one of us on a ride that we don’t seem to be getting off of anytime soon. Be gentle with yourself and with everyone else. And if you need to, take that catnap.

Thank you Andrew for the photo. There is no one on earth I would rather be doing this life with. ♥️

node.text:
Let’s set the record straight on FIV tests in young kittens! Did you know that if a young kitten tests positive for FIV, it is very likely that they are actually FIV negative? Read my brand new article & watch my new video to learn why FIV tests are so inaccurate in young kittens.

Read/watch here: KittenLady.org/fiv

This week multiple people reached out to me to say that they couldn’t adopt out a kitten because they had tested positive for FIV [cue my brain exploding! 🤯] It felt important to me to put out a resource for foster parents and adopters that explains FIV testing in kittens in a simple format so that it doesn’t have to feel so daunting or confusing. Please read the article or watch the video to learn more! This is just a short clip from a 5 minute long video. See the whole thing at KittenLady.org/fiv (or simply click the link in my bio!) ♥️
